{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17658530","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17658530"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:49:56+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:49:56+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20764"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20764"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13639"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96917"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13639","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13639"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79532"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"11657"},{"type":"tags","id":"12461"},{"type":"tags","id":"12552"},{"type":"tags","id":"12620"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"32800"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32801"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96917","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96917"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old man with a history of intravenous heroin use presents with severe respiratory distress. Chest radiograph shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates. At autopsy, lung tissue reveals numerous granulomas containing multinucleated giant cells.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most likely to be observed when examining these lung granulomas under polarised light microscopy?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemosiderin deposits","Acid-fast bacilli","Fungal hyphae","Birefringent talc particles","Calcium oxalate crystals"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct finding would be \u003Cstrong\u003Ebirefringent talc particles\u003C/strong\u003E within the granulomas. Heroin sold on the street is commonly cut (diluted) with substances such as talc. When injected intravenously, these particles can travel through the bloodstream and become trapped in the pulmonary microvasculature. The body responds by forming foreign-body granulomas around these particles, with multinucleated giant cells attempting to engulf the foreign material. Under polarised light microscopy, talc crystals appear as birefringent (doubly refractive) particles, often within foreign-body giant cells.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECalcium oxalate crystals\u003C/strong\u003E are typically associated with ethylene glycol poisoning or certain fungal infections, not heroin use.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHaemosiderin deposits\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as golden-brown pigment and are associated with previous haemorrhage, not directly with heroin-induced granulomas.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAcid-fast bacilli\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate mycobacterial infection such as tuberculosis. While intravenous drug users are at increased risk for tuberculosis, the granulomas described are foreign-body type rather than infectious.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFungal hyphae\u003C/strong\u003E would indicate a fungal infection. Although opportunistic fungal infections can occur in intravenous drug users, the described granulomas are consistent with foreign-body reaction to talc rather than fungal infection.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPulmonary complications in heroin users include pulmonary oedema, septic emboli from endocarditis, lung abscesses, opportunistic infections, and foreign-body granulomas from talc and other adulterants. These granulomas can also be found in the mononuclear phagocyte system, particularly in the spleen, liver, and lymph nodes that drain the upper extremities.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Heroin causes pulmonary complications including oedema, septic emboli, lung abscesses, opportunistic infections, and foreign-body granulomas.","Foreign-body granulomas in heroin users are primarily caused by talc and other adulterants used to cut the drug.","Talc crystals in granulomas can be visualised using polarised light microscopy, often found within foreign-body giant cells.","Heroin-related pathology stems from the drug\u0027s pharmacologic action, reactions to adulterants, hypersensitivity reactions, and infections from contaminated needles."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 9; page 424-425."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79532"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79532","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79532"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-03T14:06:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-03T14:09:08+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13639"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96917"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"11657","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11657"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam